Hexagons, moths, and light - Full work flow.¶

Oct 16, 2019, Lauren Chan¶

http://strimas.com/spatial/hexagonal-grids/

This is working for the most part, though cumbersome and for just play data. BUT, it has all the bits so that we can do what we need for future analyses...

Note: This analysis requires make_grid.r It's the second make_grid.r on the tutorial, but can be downloaded here as well: https://github.com/laurenchan/notebook/blob/master/citizen_sci/make_grid.r

It also requires the light layer which is about 750 MB and too big to post here, but which can be downloaded from here: https://pacificu.box.com/s/p46z3f267ewpmx9yru1no2n55tlzw2hy

Load USA map¶

Retrieve map using getData command which retrieves from the GADM database.

In [37]:
study_area <- getData("GADM", country = "USA", level = 0, path="data/hex-grids") %>%
    disaggregate %>% 
    geometry

Remove islands and clean up (this is from fishnet/hex tutorial. May not be appropriate for our study. Need to decide.

In [38]:
study_area <- sapply(study_area@polygons, slot, "area") %>% 
  {which(. == max(.))} %>% 
  study_area[.]

Clipping the study area. I think this has to be done before projecting. Will need to make sure that it doesn't create strange artifacts.

Overlay hexagonal grids¶

In [41]:
source("make_grid.r")

Convert the study area to raster. Will need to change the UTM zone accordingly for the projection to be correct

In [42]:
study_area_utm <- CRS("+proj=utm +zone=14 +datum=WGS84 +units=km +no_defs") %>% 
  spTransform(study_area, .)

Make the hex grid for the UTM study area. Cell area is in km. Need to be smart about the scale we are looking at relative to the resolution of the raster data and the biology of the organisms.

In [43]:
hex_grid <- make_grid(study_area_utm, type = "hexagonal", cell_area = 625, clip = FALSE)
In [44]:
plot(study_area_utm, col = "grey50", bg = "light blue", axes = FALSE)
plot(hex_grid, border = "orange", add = TRUE)

This is from fishnets and hex tutorial...¶

I don't totally understand what is happening here, but it is summing like we need it to. It would be nice to generalize this to do for several species at once...

In [163]:
fill_missing <- expand.grid(id=row.names(hex_grid), stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
pt_density  <- over(hex_grid, cropdf, returnList=TRUE) %>%
    plyr::ldply(.fun = function(x) x, .id = "id") %>%
    mutate(id = as.character(id)) %>%
    count(id) %>%
    left_join(fill_missing, ., by = "id") %>%
    SpatialPolygonsDataFrame(hex_grid, .)
                
#alt
pt_den1 <- over(hex_grid, cropdf, returnList=TRUE)

Load and plot the light data. Clip to the same as the study_area_utm¶

Downloaded from https://ngdc.noaa.gov/eog/dmsp/downloadV4composites.html (I think)

I downloaded the 2013.v4 data and put a copy on Google Drive. You will need to change the path to find the file locally on your own computer.
